Computational methods
The issue of poor LP investment decisions and lack of automation is clearly solvable by computational methods mainly because it involves structured data, pattern recognition, and rule-based logic. These are all things that can be broken down and handled using decomposition and abstraction two key ideas in computational thinking.
Computational thinking was central to the design and development of this project. The problem of allocating funds to optimal liquidity pools is complex due to the dynamic nature of crypto markets, variable risk profiles, and the need for continuous automation. To handle this, I applied five core computational thinking methods: abstraction, decomposition, pattern recognition, automation, and evaluation.

Abstraction
Abstraction involves removing unnecessary detail and focusing only on the information that is needed to solve the problem. In this project, DeFi concepts like impermanent loss, price volatility, and pool risk are abstracted into four categories:
•	Low risk: stablecoin → stablecoin
•	Medium risk: stablecoin → large-cap
•	High risk: large-cap → large-cap
•	Extreme risk: low-cap → low-cap
By abstracting pools into risk tiers, the bot avoids handling complex live token correlations and instead uses clear, generalised groupings to guide allocation. Similarly, the bot treats all supported platforms (e.g. PancakeSwap, Uniswap) through a common API layer, abstracting away the differences in their interfaces.

Decomposition
Decomposition is the process of breaking a complex problem into smaller, more manageable parts. I decomposed the system into six independent modules:
1.	Data Retrieval Module: fetches LP data (ROI, token types, liquidity, etc.)
2.	Risk Classification Module: determines pool volatility based on token pair
3.	Capital Allocation Algorithm: distributes funds based on user-defined risk profile
4.	Telegram Interface: handles all bot-user communication
5.	Rebalancing Scheduler: manages timing for auto-adjustments
6.	Simulation Engine: forecasts estimated performance for each pool
Each of these modules can be developed, tested, and maintained separately, making the system easier to build and debug.

Pattern Recognition
This technique is used to spot trends and relationships in pool data that inform decision-making. For example:
•	Pools containing stablecoins tend to have lower volatility but more consistent returns.
•	Low-cap tokens often produce higher APY but with more fluctuation.
The bot uses these patterns to match pool types with the user's selected risk level. It also recognises price deviation patterns to decide when to exit or reallocate funds automatically (e.g. if price moves outside the defined range).

Automation
Automation is a key aim of the project. Once the user configures their preferences, the bot performs the following tasks autonomously:
•	Scans available LPs across chains
•	Filters based on risk and volatility settings
•	Simulates expected ROI vs risk
•	Allocates capital
•	Monitors pools and rebalances if needed
•	Sends performance updates through Telegram
This automation significantly reduces the need for manual input and allows the system to run 24/7 — which is essential for volatile crypto markets.

Evaluation
Evaluation ensures that the final product meets the intended goals and performs reliably. Each component is tested against criteria such as:
•	Accuracy: Is the bot allocating funds to pools that match the user’s selected risk tier?
•	Reliability: Does the scheduler execute rebalancing on time?
•	Usability: Can users control the bot entirely through Telegram?
•	Performance: Do ROI simulations closely match actual past performance?
In addition, unit tests are written for key functions (e.g. allocation logic, risk detection), and system testing is done using sandbox wallets with test LP data. All success criteria are directly linked to evaluation outcomes.

Conclusion
By applying computational thinking throughout the design and development process, I have created a system that is logical, modular, scalable, and user-friendly. These methods allowed me to simplify complex DeFi mechanics and build a product that meets the needs of real stakeholders in an efficient and systematic way.





Methodologies 

For this project, I’ve chosen to follow an Agile methodology, because it allows me to build and improve the system step by step which suits a Telegram bot really well. Since my bot has multiple moving parts (real-time data, user inputs, logic systems, risk filters, wallet connection, etc.), I need an approach that’s flexible and lets me make changes as I go.

Agile works by breaking the project into small tasks (sprints) that I can build and test individually. At the end of each sprint, I’ll test the feature and decide what needs to be improved or added next. This is especially useful when dealing with APIs and wallet logic, where errors or changes in external platforms are common.

A key part of the system is the ability for users to import their own wallet using a private key. This feature will be handled early in the project because it’s essential for the bot to be able to execute real transactions (allocate funds into LPs). From a programming point of view, the wallet import will be done by:
	•	Allowing the user to send a /import command in Telegram
	•	The bot will receive and securely store the private key (only temporarily, ideally using encryption in memory)
	•	It will then generate the public address and confirm the wallet is connected
	•	The private key will be used only when signing transactions, and should never be stored permanently, for security reasons

This part will be implemented in one of the first development sprints, as it’s a building block for the rest of the system.

I also considered using the Waterfall model, but that wouldn’t work well for this type of system. Waterfall is too rigid once you’ve designed everything, it’s hard to go back. But my project needs flexibility: pool APRs change, APIs might behave differently, and even user feedback might suggest changes to Telegram commands or risk logic. Agile gives me the flexibility to adjust throughout.

I’ll structure the project into sprints like:
	•	Sprint 1: Wallet import and key validation
	•	Sprint 2: Telegram command handling
	•	Sprint 3: LP data collection and filtering
	•	Sprint 4: Allocation and auto-compound logic
	•	Sprint 5: Risk rating and user configuration
	•	Sprint 6: Final testing, UX polishing, update button, and error handling

Agile also encourages continuous testing, so at each stage I’ll be checking that the logic works properly. For example, I’ll test whether the private key really links to the correct wallet address and whether the bot signs transactions correctly.

In summary, Agile is the most suitable method because it allows me to adapt the project as it grows, get feedback along the way, and focus on delivering a working system one part at a time starting with critical core features like secure wallet import.








