Limitations 
Although this system can solve a real-world problem by automating LP fund allocation, there are still some limitations due to technical complexity, system dependencies, and development scope. These limitations don’t stop the tool from working but they do show where improvements could be made with more time, resources, or experience.
Technical Limitations
	•	Smart contract interaction is limited – While my system interacts with PancakeSwap’s existing smart contracts (like the Router and MasterChef), I’m not deploying custom contracts. This means I can’t create custom vaults, automate fee structures, or handle advanced on-chain behaviours though I can still execute core DeFi functions like adding liquidity and simulating compounding.
	•	No database or persistent storage – The bot doesn’t use a database to store user preferences, history, or past performance. This means every session is stateless unless the user reuses their chat thread. There’s no long-term tracking or analytics.
	•	External API reliance – The bot depends on live data from PancakeSwap, DeFiLlama, and CoinGecko. If any of these APIs go offline, slow down, or return bad data, the bot won’t be able to accurately calculate APR or pool risk.
	•	Telegram interface limitations – Telegram works well for command-based bots, but it’s not a visual UI. Long LP lists, APR stats, or wallet summaries can become hard to read. Also, messages can go stale, so users must manually refresh using /update.

Design Limitations
	•	Simplified risk scoring – My bot groups LPs into low, medium, or high risk based on volatility, liquidity, and market cap. However, it doesn’t account for smart contract audits, rug pull history, or liquidity lock status all of which affect real-world risk.
	•	Manual compounding logic – Although the bot can simulate compounding by harvesting rewards and reinvesting them through PancakeSwap’s smart contracts, the logic is still scripted. It doesn’t adjust dynamically or optimise fees like advanced vault protocols (e.g. Beefy).

Time & Scope Limitations
	•	BSC-only integration – To keep things manageable, I focused on Binance Smart Chain and PancakeSwap only. Adding support for Ethereum, Arbitrum, or other chains would require extra API integration, contract handling, and gas logic.
	•	No on-chain analytics – There’s no way to track long-term yield, APY trends, or user performance over time. This would be useful in a real-world version, but I didn’t have time to build a dashboard or logging system.
	•	No error recovery or fallback logic – If a transaction fails (e.g. due to gas or slippage), the bot doesn’t retry or notify the user beyond the basic error message. This would need to be added for smoother UX in production.


Security Limitations
	•	Private key storage in chat memory – In my setup, the user imports their private key through Telegram, and the bot stores it in the chat context (not in a file or database). This makes it easier for the bot to keep using the key across sessions without re-importing but it also means the key is exposed unless the user deletes it.
To fix this, I’ve added a /reset command that lets the user completely wipe their session and remove the key. It works fine for a prototype, but in real use, I’d need to upgrade this to something like encrypted storage or WalletConnect integration to make it truly secure.

Conclusion
Even with these limitations, my system still works as a functional and realistic prototype. It automates LP investing, uses real data, and gives the user a usable interface to make informed decisions. Most of the limitations listed here from vault optimisation to security upgrades  are fixable with more time or funding, and could be future improvements to make the project more production-ready.



