Hardware and System Requirements
This section outlines the hardware and software requirements needed to run and interact with the automated liquidity pool allocation bot. It covers both the end-user system (Telegram-based interaction) and the developer/server system (where the bot is hosted and executed).

5.1 End-User System Requirements
The end user does not need any special hardware or software to use the system. The bot is designed to be lightweight and accessible through the Telegram messaging platform.
To use the bot, the user simply needs:
•	A device that can run the Telegram app — this includes smartphones (iOS or Android), tablets, desktop computers, or web browsers.
•	A stable internet connection, as all commands and updates are transmitted in real-time through the Telegram Bot API.
•	No installation of additional software is necessary, and all interaction happens through simple chat commands such as /allocate, /withdraw, and /set risk=medium.
Because all processing is handled server-side, the user’s device does not perform any heavy computation or require storage beyond the Telegram app itself.

5.2 Developer and Hosting Environment
The bot itself must be hosted on a server, virtual machine, or cloud environment that supports Python 3.9 or later. The system is designed to be lightweight but does benefit from reliable uptime and connectivity for uninterrupted automation.
The minimum system requirements to host the bot are:
•	A Linux-based operating system (such as Ubuntu 20.04 or newer).
•	At least 1 CPU core running at 2.0 GHz and 1 GB of RAM to run the Python environment and external API queries.
•	At least 500 MB of available storage, which is used for the bot scripts, configuration files, and logs.
•	A constant internet connection, as the bot must be able to fetch live liquidity pool data and communicate with Telegram users in real time.
•	Python 3.9 or later must be installed, along with pip for managing dependencies.
For smoother performance and future scaling, it is recommended to use a server with 2 or more CPU cores, 2–4 GB of RAM, and a high uptime cloud service provider (e.g. AWS, DigitalOcean, or Linode) offering 99.9% reliability.

5.3 Software Dependencies
The bot is built using Python and relies on several key libraries to function:
•	python-telegram-bot is used to handle communication between the bot and the Telegram user interface.
•	requests and optionally web3.py are used to fetch live liquidity pool data from platforms like PancakeSwap and Uniswap.
•	apscheduler is used to schedule recurring tasks such as daily rebalancing checks.
•	dotenv is used to store sensitive API keys and configuration variables securely.
•	pandas may also be used to process, store, and simulate LP performance data.
In addition, the bot interacts with several external APIs and services:
•	The Telegram Bot API, for sending and receiving user messages.
•	Public APIs or subgraph endpoints from Uniswap, PancakeSwap, or similar DEX platforms.
•	RPC endpoints for supported blockchains (e.g. BSC and Ethereum).
All external services are accessed securely, with proper error handling and API request limits where applicable.

5.4 Security and Maintainability
Security is handled by:
•	Keeping all sensitive data such as API keys and Telegram tokens in environment variables (via .env files), not hard coded into the bot.
•	Using simple logging to track bot behaviour, API errors, and user actions for debugging or auditing.
•	Optional Dockerisation or virtual environment setup can be used to ensure reproducibility and safe deployment across machines.
The system is designed to be maintainable by a developer with basic Python experience and can be updated by modifying individual modules (e.g. adjusting risk filters or adding support for new platforms).

Conclusion
The system has been designed to be efficient and accessible. Users can run it with nothing more than a Telegram app and an internet connection, while the developer or maintainer can host the bot on an inexpensive VPS or cloud server with minimal resources. This makes it suitable for independent investors, small teams, or future scaling to a broader user base without significantly increasing infrastructure requirements.


















Design 
Problem decomposition 
The first stage in the design process was to break the system down into a clear set of modules. This type of decomposition makes the system easier to understand, more reliable, and easier to expand later on. Because this project involves handling real capital, every part of the system must be predictable and isolated so that errors in one part cannot damage the rest of the system.
To achieve this, I decomposed the bot into two main layers:
	1.	System Core (Control & Coordination) – this includes the modules that control when the system runs, how modules communicate, and how errors are escalated.
	2.	Functional Modules (Individual Responsibilities) – these modules handle reading data, making decisions, performing on-chain transactions, updating state, and communicating with the user.
This decomposition also shows the computational methods used in the project: abstraction, iteration, decomposition, selection, and error handling.
Below is the full set of modules and what they do.

Layer 1 — System Core

1. Scheduler & Cycle Controller
This module runs every 15 seconds and controls the entire loop of the bot. It prevents overlapping cycles, handles sleep timing, timestamps each run, and checks whether the system is in safety-lock mode (meaning the fail-safe has activated). If safety-lock is enabled, the Scheduler skips all processing to avoid exposing the user to further risk.

2. Dispatcher (Module Coordinator)
The Dispatcher forwards outputs from one module to the next. It ensures the correct sequence: load config → fetch LP data → compare with previous cycle → make decision → execute plan → calculate PnL → update UI. This also separates each module, which increases maintainability.
3. System Monitor (Fail-Safe Controller)
This module monitors for critical errors (RPC failure, missing API responses, transaction failures, inconsistent price data). If a serious error occurs, it immediately:
	•	halts all processing
	•	converts all assets to stablecoin
	•	sends critical alerts
	•	writes safetyLock = true to Firestore
	•	exits safely
This guarantees capital protection.

Layer 2 — Functional Modules

4. Secrets & Config Manager
Securely loads the user’s private key, risk setting, compounding preference, RPC URLs and Telegram token from Google Secret Manager + Firestore. All data is validated before being used.
5. Market Data Fetcher
Uses PancakeSwap APIs, CoinGecko/Binance price feeds(if needed), and on-chain web3 calls to build a complete and current view of the LP environment. Fully validates data (null/invalid checks, timestamp checks, duplicate checks) before passing it on.
6. Delta & State Comparator
Compares the current cycle’s data to the previous cycle snapshot. Calculates APR change, TVL volatility, and price movement. Detects anomalies like sudden APR drops or suspiciously low liquidity.
7. Logic Engine (Decision Module)
Applies risk rules, threshold logic, compounding logic, and ranking logic to decide whether the bot should rebalance or compound this cycle. Produces a structured execution plan describing exactly what needs to be done.

8. Execution Engine (On-Chain Executor)
Runs the actual blockchain operations:
	•	token approvals
	•	LP removal
	•	swaps
	•	adding new LP
	•	staking
	•	verifying transaction receipts
If a transaction fails, it immediately raises a critical error flag.
9. PnL & State Analytics
Tracks cycle and cumulative PnL, gas usage, liquidity changes, net value, and position sizes. Saves everything to Firestore and updates the previous-cycle cache.
10. Notification Layer
Outputs final status to Telegram (clean summary view) and delivers detailed logs by email. Also sends critical alerts when fail-safe is activated.

Having defined all of the individual modules above, this decomposition ensures that each part of the system has a single, clearly defined responsibility. This is particularly important for a system that operates autonomously and manages real financial assets, as it reduces the likelihood that an error in one area will propagate throughout the entire system. For example, issues with market data fetching are isolated from the execution logic, and failures in the user interface do not affect on-chain operations. This separation of concerns improves reliability, simplifies debugging, and makes the system easier to test and extend in the future. It also demonstrates the use of key computational methods such as abstraction, decomposition, selection, and iteration, which are essential for solving a complex, real-world problem using a computational approach.

