Justification
The variables shown in Table 3.1.3 were selected to support a modular, safe, and traceable system design. Each variable represents a clearly defined piece of system state and is deliberately limited in scope to reduce coupling between modules. For example, configuration variables such as userConfig, riskProfile, and compoundEnabled are loaded once at the start of each cycle and are treated as read-only by decision-making modules, which prevents accidental modification during execution.
Runtime variables such as lpMetrics, priceFeed, and executionPlan are stored in memory only and recalculated every cycle to ensure decisions are based on current market conditions. This design choice avoids reliance on stale data and supports the iterative nature of the 15-second execution loop. In contrast, persistent variables such as previousCycleSnapshot, totalPnL, and safetyLock are stored in Firestore to allow continuity between cycles and to enforce fail-safe behaviour across system restarts.
Security-critical data is handled through abstraction rather than direct storage. The private key itself is never stored directly within the application; instead, a reference (privateKeySecretId) is used to retrieve the encrypted key from secure storage. This reduces the risk of accidental exposure while still allowing the execution engine to perform on-chain operations when required.
Overall, this variable design ensures that each stage of the workflow has access only to the data it requires, improving reliability, maintainability, and safety when operating with real user funds.



Algorithms and Logic Design

Scheduler & Cycle Control Algorithm

The Scheduler is responsible for controlling when the system runs and ensuring that each execution cycle is isolated, predictable, and safe. Because the system operates using real user capital, it is critical that cycles do not overlap and that execution only occurs when the system is in a valid state.

The Scheduler runs on a fixed 15-second interval, which represents a balance between responsiveness and stability. At the start of each cycle, the Scheduler checks the global safetyLock variable. If safetyLock is set to true, the cycle is immediately terminated and no further processing occurs. This ensures that once a fail-safe event has been triggered, the system cannot accidentally resume execution without explicit user intervention.

If the system is not in safety-lock mode, the Scheduler records a timestamp for the current cycle and prevents any new cycle from starting until the current one has completed. This avoids race conditions such as duplicated transactions or conflicting state updates, which could otherwise lead to financial loss.

Once these checks have passed, control is passed to the Dispatcher module, which coordinates the remaining stages of the workflow in a fixed sequence. This sequence is shown in Flowchart 3.1.1, where the Scheduler acts as the entry and exit point for each execution loop. At the end of a successful cycle, the Scheduler places the system into a controlled sleep state until the next 15-second interval begins.

This algorithm makes extensive use of iteration, as the execution cycle repeats continuously, and selection, through conditional checks such as whether safetyLock is enabled. By centralising timing and execution control within a single module, the system ensures predictable behaviour and reduces the risk of uncontrolled execution.

Pseudocode — Scheduler & Cycle Control
IF safetyLock = TRUE THEN  
    EXIT current cycle  
END IF  
SET currentTimestamp = system_time  
CALL Dispatcher  
WAIT until Dispatcher has finished execution  
Justification

This approach is suitable because it abstracts timing and control away from the functional logic of the system. Individual modules do not need to manage scheduling or concurrency, which reduces complexity and improves reliability. By enforcing a strict cycle structure, the Scheduler ensures that each decision is based on a complete and consistent snapshot of system state.


Market Data Fetching and Validation Algorithm
This algorithm is responsible for collecting all external data required for decision-making and ensuring that the data is valid before it is used anywhere else in the system. Because the system operates using live blockchain and API data, incorrect or incomplete data could result in unsafe execution. For this reason, data fetching and validation are treated as a single controlled stage within the execution cycle.

At the start of each cycle, the Market Data Fetcher retrieves liquidity pool data from PancakeSwap sources and price data from external price feeds. This includes metrics such as APR, TVL, pool identifiers, token pairs, and current token prices. All data is collected within the same cycle to ensure consistency across calculations.

Once data is retrieved, a validation phase is performed before the data is passed to downstream modules. This validation checks that responses are not null, timestamps are recent, values fall within expected ranges, and that no duplicate or inconsistent data is present. If any critical validation check fails, the algorithm immediately raises an error flag and hands control to the System Monitor, preventing unsafe decisions from being made.

Only after all validation checks pass is the data packaged into structured runtime variables (lpPoolList, lpMetrics, and priceFeed) and forwarded to the Delta & State Comparator. This ensures that all later algorithms operate on a trusted and complete dataset.

This stage uses iteration, as multiple pools and tokens are processed, and selection, through conditional validation checks that determine whether execution can safely continue.

Pseudocode — Market Data Fetching and Validation

FETCH lpPoolData from PancakeSwap
FETCH priceData from price feeds

IF lpPoolData is NULL OR priceData is NULL THEN
  RAISE critical error
  EXIT cycle
END IF

FOR EACH pool IN lpPoolData
  IF pool.apr is NULL OR pool.tvl <= 0 THEN
    RAISE critical error
    EXIT cycle
  END IF
END FOR

FOR EACH token IN priceData
  IF token.price <= 0 OR token.timestamp is outdated THEN
    RAISE critical error
    EXIT cycle
  END IF
END FOR

STORE validated data in runtime structures
PASS data to Delta Comparator


Justification
Separating data fetching from decision logic ensures that invalid or incomplete data cannot influence execution. By validating all external inputs before they are used, the system reduces the risk of incorrect rebalancing decisions caused by API failures, stale prices, or malformed responses. This approach is essential for maintaining safety and reliability when operating autonomously in a volatile and decentralised environment.
Decision-Making and Rebalancing Algorithm

This algorithm is responsible for deciding whether the system should take action during the current execution cycle. Unlike the previous stages, which focus on control and data integrity, this stage evaluates market conditions and user preferences to determine what, if anything, should be executed on-chain.

At the start of this stage, the algorithm receives validated market data and the previous cycle snapshot from the Delta & State Comparator. The first step is to calculate relative changes between cycles, such as APR movement, TVL change, and price volatility. These values are used instead of raw figures to reduce sensitivity to short-term noise and to ensure decisions are based on meaningful trends rather than isolated spikes.

Once deltas have been calculated, the algorithm applies a risk-based filtering process. Liquidity pools that do not meet the user’s selected risk profile are removed from consideration. For example, pools with low liquidity or excessive volatility may be excluded when the user has selected a low-risk configuration. This filtering stage reduces the decision space and prevents the system from considering unsuitable options.

After filtering, the remaining pools are ranked using a weighted scoring approach based on metrics such as adjusted APR, liquidity depth, and stability. The highest-ranked pool is then compared against the user’s current position. If the difference between the current pool and the best available alternative exceeds a predefined threshold, the algorithm determines that a rebalance is required. If compounding is enabled and no rebalance condition is met, the algorithm checks whether rewards should be compounded instead.

The output of this process is an explicit decision state (NO_ACTION, REBALANCE, or COMPOUND) along with a structured execution plan describing the exact actions required. If no conditions are met, the system takes no action and proceeds to the end of the cycle.

This algorithm makes heavy use of selection, through conditional decision rules, and iteration, as multiple pools are evaluated and compared during each cycle.


Pseudocode — Decision-Making and Rebalancing
CALCULATE deltaMetrics using currentData and previousCycleSnapshot
FILTER pools based on riskProfile
FOR EACH pool IN filteredPools
  CALCULATE poolScore
END FOR
SELECT bestPool with highest poolScore
IF bestPool ≠ currentPool AND scoreDifference > rebalanceThreshold THEN
  SET decision = REBALANCE
  BUILD executionPlan for rebalance
ELSE IF compoundEnabled = TRUE AND rewardsAvailable = TRUE THEN
  SET decision = COMPOUND
  BUILD executionPlan for compounding
ELSE
  SET decision = NO_ACTION
END IF
RETURN decision and executionPlan

Justification

Using a threshold-based and risk-filtered decision process prevents unnecessary transactions and reduces exposure to short-term market volatility. By explicitly separating decision logic from execution logic, the system remains predictable and easier to test. This approach ensures that on-chain actions are only taken when there is a clear and justifiable benefit, which is essential when operating autonomously with real user funds.








Fail-Safe and Error Handling Algorithm

The fail-safe algorithm is designed to protect user funds in the event of critical system failures. Because the system operates autonomously and interacts directly with blockchain infrastructure, it must be able to respond immediately to unsafe conditions without relying on user intervention.

Throughout each execution cycle, the System Monitor continuously listens for error signals raised by other modules. These errors include, but are not limited to: RPC connection failures, invalid or inconsistent market data, failed on-chain transactions, and unexpected execution states. Not all errors are treated equally; only errors classified as critical will trigger the fail-safe mechanism.

When a critical error is detected, normal execution is immediately halted. The algorithm then initiates an emergency sequence that converts all active positions into a stablecoin. This is done to minimise further exposure to market volatility while the system is in an unsafe state. Once this operation has completed, the system records the event, activates the safetyLock variable, and prevents all future execution cycles from running.

After the fail-safe sequence has finished, the user is notified through the Telegram interface and a detailed error log is stored for later inspection. The system remains in safety-lock mode until the user explicitly resets it, ensuring that execution cannot silently resume after a serious failure.

This algorithm relies heavily on selection, as it must distinguish between recoverable and non-recoverable errors, and abstraction, as complex error conditions are reduced to a small set of critical triggers.








Pseudocode — Fail-Safe and Error Handling
IF criticalErrorDetected = TRUE THEN
  HALT all processing
  EXECUTE emergencySwap to stablecoin
  SET safetyLock = TRUE
  LOG error details
  NOTIFY user
  EXIT system
END IF

Justification
This approach ensures that capital protection is prioritised over continued operation. By automatically converting assets to stablecoin and locking the system after a critical failure, the risk of cascading errors and further losses is significantly reduced. Separating fail-safe logic from normal execution also makes the system easier to reason about and test, which is essential for a system that manages real financial value.


User Interface Design
The user interface for this system is implemented entirely through a Telegram bot. This design choice was made to prioritise accessibility, speed, and ease of use, while avoiding the complexity and overhead of building a traditional web-based interface. Most users interacting with decentralised finance tools are already familiar with Telegram-based bots, which makes this interface suitable for the target audience.
The Telegram interface acts as a control and monitoring layer, not as a place where core logic is executed. All sensitive operations, such as decision-making and on-chain execution, occur within the system core. The interface simply allows the user to view system state, adjust settings, and receive notifications.





Interface Structure
The interface is message-based and consists of three main components:
1.	Status Display
o	Shows current wallet balance
o	Displays active liquidity pool and position size
o	Shows current cycle PnL and cumulative PnL
o	Indicates whether compounding is enabled
o	Displays system state (active / paused / safety-lock)
This information is presented in a structured text layout to ensure clarity and reduce cognitive load.
2.	User Input Controls
o	Buttons are provided for:
	enabling or disabling compounding
	changing risk profile (low / medium / high)
	pausing or resuming the bot
	resetting the system after a safety-lock event
o	Buttons are chosen instead of free-text input to prevent invalid commands and reduce user error.
3.	Notification and Alert System
o	Normal execution updates are sent after each completed cycle
o	Critical alerts are sent immediately if the fail-safe is triggered
o	Messages are updated in place where possible to avoid clutter and outdated information
This interface design is supported by Flowchart 3.1.5, which shows how user interactions feed into the system and how system outputs are reflected back to the user.





Justification

Using Telegram as the interface abstracts away the complexity of front-end development while still providing a responsive and interactive user experience. The separation between interface and system logic improves security, as the interface never directly handles private keys or executes transactions. By restricting user input to predefined actions, the system reduces the risk of incorrect configuration and ensures predictable behavior.


Testing Strategy
The testing strategy for this project is designed to ensure that the system behaves correctly under normal conditions and, more importantly, fails safely under abnormal conditions. Because the system interacts with live blockchain infrastructure and real user capital, testing focuses on correctness, reliability, and risk containment rather than performance alone.
Testing is planned to take place at three levels: unit testing, integration testing, and system-level testing. Each level targets a different type of failure and helps ensure that issues are detected as early as possible.
Unit Testing
Unit testing is used to verify the behaviour of individual modules in isolation. This includes testing logic such as:
•	risk filtering and pool ranking calculations
•	decision thresholds for rebalancing and compounding
•	validation rules for incoming market data
•	safety-lock activation conditions
Mock data is used to simulate API responses and on-chain data so that logic can be tested deterministically without relying on live services. This ensures that core algorithms behave as expected before they are integrated into the full system.
Integration Testing
Integration testing focuses on how modules interact with each other. This includes testing:
•	the handoff between data fetching and decision-making
•	the passing of execution plans to the execution engine
•	correct state updates between cycles
•	interaction between the system core and the notification layer
These tests ensure that data flows correctly through the system workflow shown in Flowchart 3.1.1 and that no module produces outputs that break downstream logic.
System and Fail-Safe Testing
System-level testing is used to verify end-to-end behaviour. This includes running full execution cycles using controlled inputs and observing:
•	correct cycle timing
•	correct execution decisions
•	correct user notifications
Special emphasis is placed on fail-safe testing. Faults such as API timeouts, invalid data, and transaction failures are deliberately injected to confirm that:
•	execution is halted immediately
•	assets are converted to stablecoin
•	the system enters safety-lock mode
•	users are notified correctly
This ensures that the system behaves predictably even in worst-case scenarios.

Justification
This layered testing strategy reduces risk by catching errors early and ensuring that failures are contained. By testing both normal operation and failure conditions, the system can be validated not just for correctness, but also for safety. This is essential for a system that operates autonomously and manages real financial value.







Traceability to Success Criteria

This subsection explains how the design decisions made in this section ensure that the system can be evaluated accurately against the success criteria defined in the Analysis section. By explicitly linking design features to measurable outcomes, it ensures that the final evaluation is objective rather than subjective.

Each major component of the system has been designed to directly support one or more success criteria. For example, the Scheduler and Cycle Control algorithm ensures that the system operates reliably at fixed intervals, which supports success criteria related to system stability and correct execution timing. The Market Data Fetching and Validation algorithm supports criteria relating to data accuracy and decision reliability, as only validated data is allowed to influence execution.

The Decision-Making and Rebalancing algorithm supports success criteria related to profitability and risk control by ensuring that rebalancing only occurs when predefined thresholds are met and user-selected risk settings are respected. This allows success to be measured by observing whether unnecessary trades are avoided and whether the system behaves in line with user configuration.

The Fail-Safe and Error Handling algorithm directly supports safety-related success criteria. Its ability to halt execution, convert assets to stablecoin, and lock the system after a critical error provides a clear and testable condition for capital protection. This can be evaluated by deliberately injecting failures and observing whether the correct safety behaviour occurs.

The Telegram-based user interface supports usability-related success criteria. Because all key system states, balances, and decisions are visible to the user in a structured format, usability can be measured through user feedback and task completion without requiring technical knowledge of the underlying system.

Overall, the design ensures that every success criterion has a corresponding mechanism within the system that can be tested and verified. This traceability makes the evaluation stage clear, measurable, and aligned with the original aims of the project.

